   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28609_1827_11_18_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1827-11-18">Nov.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 18.<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1827.</date>
               </dateline>
               <lb/>
               <salute>
                  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">friend</persName>
                  <lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I must trouble you to read the<lb/>
               enclosed letters from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName> to<lb/>
               me and my last to him -<lb/>
               -about <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early2">Harry and Lucy</title> -
               Letter N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>. 1 - and 2 will show
               you that I took every precaution
               to assure myself that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName>
               was not a loser by my chang
               ing the title of H &amp; L - I have
               not kept any copies of my letters
               but I daresay <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName> has
               my letter of Feb 1826 in wh<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>
               I offered then to deduct from
               the copy right whatever he after
               the promised years experience
               sh<hi rend="superscript">d </hi>find <add>or <hi rend="underline">think</hi>
               </add> he had lost by the
               book - His own answer <date when="1826-02-23">Feb 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
               1826</date> - declines accepting my<lb/>
               proffered deduction &amp; only<lb/>
               accepts my offer of delaying<lb/>
               payment -<lb/>
               <date when="1826-12">Dec.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 1826</date> - he again asks me to<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28609_1827_11_18_page02.jpg"/>
               
               delay the promised payment<lb/>
               for another year - but without<lb/>
               even hinting that he had lost<lb/>
               by the publication - I acceded<lb/>
               to the delay - &amp; told him (of course)<lb/>
               that I would not take the <unclear>int</unclear>
               <lb/>
               which he offered -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I make no doubt that<lb/>
               his statements of <hi rend="underline">accounts</hi> are<lb/>
               true - but I think his losses<lb/>
               may in great measure arise<lb/>
               from his own mismanagement<lb/>
               for which I am not answerable.<lb/>
               - I hope my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> you<lb/>
               will approve of my letter to<lb/>
               him &amp; of my not making<lb/>
               any hesitation in acceding<lb/>
               to his proposal though I certainly<lb/>
               do not feel that I am bound<lb/>
               either by promise or honor<lb/>
               to accede to it -<lb/>
               I leave the letter in your<lb/>
               hands to deliver or not as you<lb/>
               think proper - If you see any<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28609_1827_11_18_page03.jpg"/>
                  
               thing in it that you as my friend<lb/>
               wish altered I am sure you<lb/>
               will tell me so -<lb/>
               Fortunately - or I may say prudently<lb/>
               I have not pledged or spent any<lb/>
               part of this <unclear>100 £</unclear>- though I own<lb/>
               I depend on its payment as<lb/>
               securely the ensuing <choice>
                  <abbr>Jan.<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>
                  </abbr>
                  <reg>January</reg>
               </choice> as<lb/>
               if it had been in bank - I had<lb/>
               intended to have had the <choice>
                  <orig>plea-<lb/>
                  sure</orig>
                  <reg>pleasure</reg>
               </choice> of giving it and that is all<lb/>
               I lose in reality -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>When <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrewD1">Doctor Brewster</persName> was<lb/>
               here a few months ago he kindly<lb/>
               urged me to let him and a<lb/>
               society of literary men at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edinburgh_STK">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Edin<lb/>
                  burgh</orig>
                     <reg>Edinburgh</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> publish any future<lb/>
               book for me - he assured me<lb/>
               that as they employ printers<lb/>
               without the <hi rend="underline">middleman</hi> called<lb/>
               a publisher they find they can<lb/>
               afford to give more copyright<lb/>
               than is usually given by publishers<lb/>
               - When I told him what <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName>
               <lb/>
               was to give me for <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early2">H &amp; L</title> - he<lb/>
               said we could give you a third<lb/>
               more - When he spoke of a future<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28609_1827_11_18_page04.jpg"/>
               <del>publication</del>
               <add>book</add> which I had told him<lb/>
               I was thinking of beginning to<lb/>
               write he urged me to consider<lb/>
               my own interest I replied that<lb/>
               I felt myself engaged to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName>
               <lb/>
               and that whether engaged or<lb/>
               not I never would quit him<lb/>
               as long as he should continue<lb/>
               to wish to publish for me -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>But what he has now written<lb/>
               to me I think alters the case -<lb/>
               and as he assures me that he<lb/>
               is no gainer by my publications<lb/>
               do you not think I am now<lb/>
               right in telling him as I do in<lb/>
               my letter that all accounts are<lb/>
               closed between us? -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>You perceive that I have<lb/>
               not hinted to him anything<lb/>
               of my intention to write a new<lb/>
               work because I did not think<lb/>
               it handsome to do so on his<lb/>
               account or prudent on mine<lb/>
               - but I am anxious to know<lb/>
               your opinion on this point for my<lb/>
               own satisfaction - I must<lb/>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28609_1827_11_18_page05.jpg"/>
                  
               add my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> for your satisfaction<lb/>
               that whatever little present mortification<lb/>
               I may feel in hearing that the sale of<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early2">Harry &amp; Lucy</title> is so <hi rend="underline">slow</hi>, is nothing in <choice>
                  <orig>compar-<lb/>
                  ison</orig>
                  <reg>comparison</reg>
               </choice> with the heartfelt pleasure I have in<lb/>
               knowing that those whom I consider as the<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">best</hi> judges approve of the book &amp; think it <choice>
                  <orig>wor-<lb/>
                  -thy</orig>
                  <reg>worthy</reg>
               </choice> of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early2">the first part of H &amp; L</title> - I feel that the<lb/>
               infinite pains which you &amp; my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName>
               <lb/>
               and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> bestowed upon it have<lb/>
               not been thrown away - It has gained far more<lb/>
               credit in the literary world than I or I dare<lb/>
               say than you ever expected - But it was not<lb/>
               written either for fame or money - The object I had<lb/>
               in view has been fully &amp; to me delightfully <choice>
                  <orig>ac-<lb/>
                  complished</orig>
                  <reg>accomplished</reg>
               </choice> - I would go over again all the<lb/>
               labor to have this feeling; and what is more -<lb/>
               I would willingly again accept from you<lb/>
               my dear friend all your labor &amp; time &amp;<lb/>
               anxiety - I cannot more strongly express<lb/>
               the value of my self-satisfaction - a feeling<lb/>
               I hope distinct from either pride or vanity<lb/>
            </p>
            <lb/>
            <closer>
               I am most gratefully &amp; affectionately<lb/>
               Your obliged<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28609_1827_11_18_page06.jpg"/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. Beaufort</persName>R N.</addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
